<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-895-854  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 895 854.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  Nov 6 1989 v217 n20 p42(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fusion can bring fiber to the home. (fusion splicing andfiber-optic communication systems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Whapham, Robert.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Advances in fusion splicing equipment can make fusion a viablechoice to bring fiber to the home.andP;  Technically, a fused joint hasalmost the same physical and optical properties as the originalmaterial.andP;  Mechanically, spliced joints can loosen over time.andO;Among the most advanced equipment currently available is theFiberlight Micro Fusion Splicer from Foundation Instruments.andP;  Thissplicer is 4 inches by 6 inches and weighs less than 2 pounds.andO;Operators with minimal training can produce splices with anaverage performance loss of less than 0.1 dB on multimode fibersand 0.2 dB on single-mode fibers.andP;  An initial investment of $5,000plus 90 cents per splice reaches break-even as compared withmechanical splicing at about 1,000 splices, or about $7.50 asplice.andP;  Fusion costs continue to drop while mechanical costsremain static.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Foundation Instruments (products).andO;Product:   Foundation Instruments Fiberlign Micro Fusion Splicer (usage).andO;Topic:     Fiber opticsCommunications EquipmentMaintenanceNew TechniqueCablesTelephone systems.andO;Feature:   illustrationchartgraph.andO;Caption:   Example of a branched fiber distribution network for FTTHapplications. (chart)Cost curves for mechanical and fusion splicing of loop fiber.andO;(graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>